# 9. 一緒に

Principal: Mafuyu Asahina.
Principal: Congratulations on placing third at the Kanto High Schools Invitational Archery Tournament. I hereby award you with this certificate to mark your great achievement.
Mafuyu: Thank you very much.
Classmates: She placed third! She really is amazing...!
Classmates: She's top of the class too, and she even won an award the other day for that essay she wrote. She really can do it all!
Kanade: Wow...
Mafuyu: I'm sorry for the wait. Especially after I invited you to walk home together.
Kanade: No, that's okay. But what did that teacher need from you?
Mafuyu: So, the school's apparently revising the pamphlet...
Mafuyu: They wanted to know if it'd be okay for them to include a photo of me from today's ceremony in the gym.
Kanade: I see...
Kanade: You really are an amazing person, Asahina.
Mafuyu: Huh?
Kanade: Between the archery club and school in general, you keep achieving all these incredible results.
Kanade: All I know how to do is compose songs. So I'm just really impressed...
Mafuyu: Don't say that, Yoisaki. Your songs...
Mafuyu: They're a source of warmth for so many people.
Kanade: Warmth, huh...?
Kanade: Thank you. I didn't realize that's how they sound to you, Asahina.
Kanade: But my songs still leave a lot to be desired. I'm still nothing compared to my dad.
Mafuyu: I'm sure that's not true...
Mafuyu: I know. Are there any things that you'd like to try other than composing songs?
Kanade: Things I'd like to try?
Kanade: I don't know...
Mafuyu: Whatever is fine. Anything that interests you.
Kanade: Hmm...
Kanade: Oh, I am a little interested in the brass band.
Mafuyu: The brass band?
Kanade: Yes, since playing music with others seems like fun. I feel like doing so would help broaden my horizons as a composer.
Kanade: Also, I'm not very good at writing essays... Expanding my vocabulary and learning how to write better should help me produce better lyrics.
Kanade: And I'd like to learn how to draw.
Mafuyu: Hehe. Is that also to become a better composer?
Kanade: That's right. I sometimes draw inspiration for songs from art. I feel like drawing things myself would let me see things from a different perspective.
Mafuyu: I see...
Mafuyu: Then, you should try doing all those things.
Kanade: Wait, all...?
Mafuyu: Yes. It's like you said, who knows what might be of use to you?
Kanade: Still, all of them...? I don't know if I can.
Mafuyu: Then, I'll help you. We can try them together.
Kanade: Asahina...
Kanade: Okay, I'll give them all a try.
Kanade: So... In modern society, music serves as a source of happiness and relaxation for people...
Mafuyu: Good. Your writing has improved quite a lot compared to where you were initially.
Kanade: I'm starting to find it kind of fun thanks to you, Asahina.
Kanade: Composing text is just like composing songs. I just need to write what I feel. And while I'm writing, the “melody” just seems to naturally come together as I go.
Kanade: Lately, lyrics have been popping into my head before any music. I feel like I can go about composing in so many different ways now.
Mafuyu: I see... Hehe. In that case, I'll be looking forward to listening to your next song.
Kanade: I don't think I've drawn this right. But what's wrong with it?
Mafuyu: Hmm... The background looks fine from my point of view, but it does feel a little cluttered, maybe.
Kanade: Yes, I had a feeling. I wanted to add some trees to the foreground, but I'm not sure there's any room now...
???: In that case, why don't you just draw what you want to the most?
Kanade: What I want to the most...?
Ena: Yeah. You're trying to draw everything, so you're losing focus and losing impact.
Ena: You're Yoisaki, right? Can you tell me what you're trying to capture?
Kanade: Oh, so... I wanted to show the way the sun sparkles on the lake in between the big trees...
Ena: I see. Then, you should focus more on how the light reflects off the water's surface. Like this...
Kanade: Wow, that's incredible... It looks so much better already. But all you did was draw a couple lines.
Ena: This is pretty basic stuff, you know.
Kanade: Oh, I see. Thank you, Shinonome.
Airi: Hehe. Ena looks like she's having fun.
Mafuyu: I agree. Momoi, thank you again for introducing Shinonome to us.
Airi: No problem. Ena has a habit of staying cooped up in her room if she's not given opportunities to meet people like this.
Airi: And I think she needs breaks like this too.
Mafuyu: I see...
Brass Band President: Alright, we'll start playing in thirty minutes! We've got a few students here to observe, so we'll be taking it easy today.
Students: Okay!
Mafuyu: Hehe. You seem a little anxious, Yoisaki.
Kanade: Oh...yes. I'm mostly excited. I am worried about whether I'll be able to do it right, though.
Mafuyu: This is also my first time, so let's do our best together.
Kanade: Yes, let's both do our best...!
Kanade: Thank you, Asahina.
Mafuyu: Huh?
Kanade: If you hadn't brought me here, Asahina, then I probably never would've actually done this.
Mafuyu: Then, let's have as much fun as we can today.
Kanade: Yes, let's!
